tragon\n        mapped_data \u003d map_to_icositetragon(data)\n\n        # Plot the mapped data\n        plot_icositetragonal(mapped_data)\n    else:\n        print(\"Failed to generate data.\")\n```\n\n### 3. Enhancements and Considerations:\n- **Dynamic Data Length**: The example assumes a set length for the icositetragon mapping. If data length varies, consider how to best represent that within your polygon structure.\n- **Interactive Features**: Use interactive plotting features in Plotly to allow users to hover over points and see detailed information about each data point.\n- **Documentation**: Continue to document your functions, explaining the logic behind the transformations and visualizations to ensure clarity for future reference or collaboration.\n\n### Final Thoughts:\nYou\u0027ve laid a strong foundation with data generation and caching. The next steps will bring your financial data analysis pipeline to life, integrating sophisticated mapping and visualization techniques. Should you have any queries or require assistance during this implementation stage, feel free to reach out! Happy coding!",
