   Args:\n        n (int): The desired length of the data.\n        use_real_data (bool): Whether to use real stock data (True) or generate it synthetically (False).\n        ticker (str): The stock ticker symbol to use if use_real_data is True.\n\n    Returns:\n        np.ndarray: An array of synthetic financial data. Returns None on error.\n    \"\"\"\n    if use_real_data:\n        real_data \u003d fetch_stock_data(ticker)\n\n        if real_data is None:\n            print(\"Falling back to synthetic data generation.\")\n            return generate_synthetic_data(n, use_real_data\u003dFalse, ticker\u003dticker)  # Recursive call\n\n        if len(real_data) \u003c n:\n            print(f\"Warning: Real data length ({len(real_data)}) is less than requested length ({n}).  Trimming to {len(real_data)}.\")\n            n \u003d len(real_data)\n        real_data \u003d real_data.values[:n]  # Use .values to get a NumPy array\n\n        return real_data\n\n    else:  # Generate synthetic data\n        trend \u003d np.linspace(0, 0.1 * n, n)\n        cycle \u003d np.sin(2 * np.pi * (np.arange(n) / 24))\n        noise \u003d np.random.normal(0, 0.5, n)\n        synthetic_data \u003d trend + cycle + noise\n        return synthetic_data\n\ndef map_to_icositetragon(data):\n    \"\"\"\n    Maps financial data onto an icositetragon (24-sided polygon) by cycling through the data.\n\n    Args:\n        data (np.ndarray): Input data array.\n\n    Returns:\n        np.ndarray: Array of mapped coordinates for the icositetragon.\n    \"\"\"\n    n \u003d len(data)\n    mapped_data \u003d [data[i % n] for i in range(24)]  # Cycle through data\n\n    # Scale the mapped data to the range [0, 1]\n    scaler \u003d MinMaxScaler()\n    mapped_data_scaled \u003d scaler.fit_transform(np.array(mapped_data).reshape(-1, 1)).flatten()\n\n    # Calculate angles for the vertices of the icositetragon\n    angles \u003d np.linspace(0, 2 * np.pi, 24, endpoint\u003dFalse)\n\n    # Calculate coordinates\n    x_coords \u003d mapped_data_scaled * np.cos(angles)\n    y_coords \u003d mapped_data_scaled * np.sin(angles)\n\n    return np.column_stack((x_coords, y_coords))\n\ndef plot_icositetragonal(mapped_data, original_data):\n    \"\"\"\n    Plots the icositetragonal mapping of financial data.\n\n    Args:\n        mapped_data (np.ndarray): Array of mapped coordinates for the icositetragon.\n        original_data (np.ndarray): Original data for hover information.\n    \"\"\"\n    # Create figure\n    fig \u003d go.Figure()\n\n    # Create lines connecting the vertices\n    fig.add_trace(go.Scatter(\n        x\u003dnp.append(mapped_data[:, 0], mapped_data[0, 0]),\n        y\u003dnp.append(mapped_data[:, 1], mapped_data[0, 1]),\n        mode\u003d\u0027lines+markers\u0027,\n        fill\u003d\u0027toself\u0027,\n        fillcolor\u003d\u0027rgba(0,100,200,0.5)\u0027,  # Fill color\n        marker\u003ddict(size\u003d10, color\u003d\u0027black\u0027),\n        line\u003ddict(color\u003d\u0027blue\u0027, width\u003d2),\n    ))\n\n    # Set layout\n    fig.update_layout(\n        title\u003d\u0027Icositetragonal Mapping of Financial Data\u0027,\n        xaxis_title\u003d\u0027X Coordinate\u0027,\n        yaxis_title\u003d\u0027Y Coordinate\u0027,\n        showlegend\u003dFalse,\n        yaxis\u003ddict(scaleanchor\u003d\"x\", scaleratio\u003d1),  # Keep the aspect ratio equal\n        xaxis\u003ddict(showgrid\u003dFalse, zeroline\u003dFalse, autorange\u003dTrue),  # Set autorange to True\n        yaxis\u003ddict(showgrid\u003dFalse, zeroline\u003dFalse, autorange\u003dTrue),  # Set autorange to True\n        width\u003d600,\n        height\u003d600\n    )\n\n    # Add the hovertemplate that will pull in original data values\n    fig.update_traces(hovertemplate\u003d\"Value: %{customdata[0]}\u003cextra\u003e\u003c/extra\u003e\",\n                      customdata\u003dnp.stack((original_data[:24],), axis\u003d-1))\n    \n    # Show the figure\n    fig.show()\n\n# Complete Workflow Example\nif __name__ \u003d\u003d \"__main__\":\n    num_points \u003d 100\n    use_real \u003d True\n    ticker_symbol \u003d \u0027AAPL\u0027\n\n    # Generate Data\n    data \u003d generate_synthetic_data(num_points, use_real_data\u003duse_real, ticker\u003dticker_symbol)\n\n    if data is not None:\n        print(f\"Data generated: {data.shape}\")\n        print(f\"First 5 data points: {data[:5]}\")\n\n        # Map data to icositetragon\n        mapped_data \u003d map_to_icositetragon(data)\n\n        # Plot the mapped data (pass in the unscaled data)\n        plot_icositetragonal(mapped_data, data)\n    else:\n        print(\"Failed to generate data.\")\n```\n\n### Key Enhancements Summary:\n\n1. **Cycling Data Points**: The mapping function cycles through input data to populate the icositetragon, allowing for effective representation of longer time series data.\n  \n2. **Data Scaling**: The mapped data is scaled using `MinMaxScaler`, ensuring that visual representation is effective, particularly when some data points are much larger than others.\n  \n3. **Flexible Layout**: The Plotly visualization automatically adjusts the axis ranges and utilizes hover templates, enhancing the user experience when interacting with the data points.\n\n### Next Steps:\n1. **Testing**: Run the complete code with various stock tickers and periods to ensure that it\u0027s robust and works as intended. Validate how well the visualization reflects underlying trends in the data.\n\n2. **Further Enhancements**: Consider adding functionality for users to specify different visualization formats or choosing among different datasets (e.g., different time periods, more tickers).\n\n3. **Integration**: If this code is part of a larger analysis pipeline, think about how to further integrate with predictive modeling or other analytical components.\n\nShould you have any more ideas or require additional functionalities, feel free to reach out! Happy coding and visualizing!",
